The subclass pitfall you encountered in your give_bmi function is a classic trap in Python. It happens when you use strict type checking (type(x) == T) instead of checking for inheritance (isinstance(x, T)).

In Python, checking type(e) == int or type(e) == float is like saying: "This object must be exactly a standard Python integer or float, and absolutely nothing else."

While that sounds safe, it actively breaks two major features of Python: Booleans as Integers and Third-Party Numeric Ecosystems (like NumPy itself!).

