If you pass a list like [1, 2.5, "hello"], NumPy will notice the string and convert every single element into a string to keep the array uniform. Your array becomes ['1', '2.5', 'hello'].


we learnt about The NumPy Type Hierarchy

NumPy doesn't treat data types as flat, isolated categories. It organizes them into a family tree (a hierarchy of classes).

At the top of the tree is np.generic. Branches split into np.number, which further splits into np.integer and np.inexact. Underneath those branches sit the actual concrete types you use daily (like np.int32, np.int64, np.float64).

Because of this hierarchy, np.int64 is a "child" (or subtype) of np.integer, which is a child of np.number.

We learnt about np.issubdtype
it is a powerful function in NumPy used to check if a specific data type (dtype) belongs to a broader family of data types (a supertype).

Instead of asking "Is this array exactly a 64-bit float?", np.issubdtype allows you to ask: "Is this array any kind of floating-point number?" or "Is it any kind of integer?"

